<!--************************************************************
Author: University of Minnesota PreCalculus Dept.
Reviewed/Remixed by: Doenet team

About the problem: Solve an absolute value equation for x. There are 3 versions of this problem:
Version 1 has form |x +/- a| = b
Version 2 has form |x +/- a| +/- d = c
Version 3 has form k|x +/- a| +/- d = c

The "Worked Example" can be hidden from view by commenting out the <hint> portion of the document.
*************************************************************-->
<problem><title/>
<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="1" to="6"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="c" from="1" to="3"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="-1" to="1" exclude="0"/>
  <math name="m" simplify>$a $b</math>
  <math name="n" simplify>$a + $c</math>
  <math name="p" simplify>x + $m</math>
  <math name="sol1" simplify>-$n - $m</math>
  <math name="sol2" simplify>$n - $m</math>
</setup>


<!--testing-->
<!-- <p>a = $a</p>
<p>b = $b</p>
<p>c = $c</p>
<p>m = $m</p>
<p>n = $n</p>
<p>p = $p</p>
<p>sol1 = $sol1</p>
<p>sol2 = $sol2</p> -->
<!--testing-->


<p>Solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
  <me>|$p| = $n</me>



<!--*********************************************
            Graphing Tool
**********************************************-->

<aside><title>Graphing tool</title>
<p>To understand this problem graphically, imagine a "<m>\color{red}{y = }</m> ", to the left of the expression you are given.</p>
  <p>Then, we would have
    <me>\color{red}{y = } |$p| = $n.</me>
  In words, this is saying that there is (we hope) one or more values, call them <m>y</m>, where <m>y = |$p|</m> and also <m>y = $n</m>. We've turned our single equation into two equations. Let's graph these two equations to see if they intersect!</p>
<sideBySide margins="5%" widths="30% 70%">
<div>
  <p>Enter the given expression to the left of the equals sign:</p> 
  <p><m>\color{red}{y = }</m><mathInput name="graphEq1"/></p>

  
  <p>Enter the given number to the right of the equals sign:</p> 
  <p><m>\color{red} {y = }</m><mathInput name="graphEq2"/></p>
  
  <p>First intersection point (drag or type):</p>
  <p><m>(x_1,y_1) =  </m></p>
  <p><m>\bigg(</m> <mathInput name="graphX1" bindValueTo="$p1.x"/> , <mathInput name="graphY1" bindValueTo="$graphEq2"/><m> \bigg)</m></p>
  <p>Second intersection point (drag or type):</p>
  <p><m>(x_2,y_2) =  </m></p>
  <p><m>\bigg(</m> <mathInput name="graphX2" bindValueTo="$p2.x"/> , <mathInput name="graphY2" bindValueTo="$graphEq2"/><m> \bigg)</m></p>
</div>

  
<graph name="g1">
  <function name="f">$graphEq1</function>
  <line name="line2" equation="y = $graphEq2" fixed styleNumber="2"/>
  <point name="p1" coords="(-1, $graphY1)" styleNumber="5">
    <constraints>
      <constrainToGrid/>
      <constrainTo>$line2</constrainTo>
    </constraints>
    <label>$p1.coords</label>
  </point>
  <point name="p2" coords="(1, $graphY2)" styleNumber="5">
    <label>$p2.coords</label>
    <constraints>
      <constrainToGrid/>
      <constrainTo>$line2</constrainTo>
    </constraints>
  </point>
</graph>
  
</sideBySide>

  <p>Notice, we've used a horizontal line on the graph to represent all values of <m>y</m> that are equal to the right-hand side (since it is a constant number).</p>
  
  <p>Where does it look like the absolute value function and the horizontal line intersect each other? Enter these locations as the "First intersection point" and "Second intersection point".</p>

</aside>  


<p>Solution(s): <m>x = </m><mathInput name="userSol1"/> or <m>x = </m> <mathInput name="userSol2"/></p>

  <answer name="ans1">
    <award name="correct" unorderedCompare>
      <when>
        <mathList>$userSol1 $userSol2</mathList> = <mathList>$sol1 $sol2</mathList>
      </when>
    </award>
    <award name="half" unorderedCompare matchPartial credit="0">
      <when>
        <mathList>$userSol1 $userSol2</mathList> = <mathList>$sol1 $sol2</mathList>
      </when>
    </award>
</answer>



