<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>
 
<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p>
<div newNamespace>
<example>
<p><em>Solve for <m>x</m>.</em></p>
  <me>|x+7| = 1</me>

<p><em>Enter all possible solutions in the answer box, separated by commas.</em></p>

  
<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>
<ul>
<li><p>We can approach this problem either algebraically or graphically. First, we'll find an answer algebraically and then check it graphically.</p></li>

  <li>
  <p><alert>Algebraic solution:</alert> Ask yourself, what does the absolute value function do? It gives the same value as its input if the input is positive, and the opposite value if the input is negative. Instead of a single value inside the absolute value function, we have an expression. Therefore, there are two cases depending on <m>x</m>:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><p>The entire expression inside the absolute value symbols could evaluate to a <em>positive</em> number when <m>x</m> is known, in which case the absolute value symbols leave the input unchanged. Algebraically, this is saying
        <md>
          <mrow>|(x + 7)| = (x+7) \amp= 1</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp= -6</mrow>
        </md>
        So, our first solution is <m>x = -6</m></p>
      </li>
      <li><p>Depending on the value of <m>x</m>, the entire expression inside the absolute value symbols could evaluate to a <em>negative</em> number, in which case the absolute value symbols would <em>reverse</em> the sign of the entire expression. Algebraically, this is saying
        <md>
          <mrow>|(x + 7)| = -(x +7) \amp= 1</mrow>
          <mrow>-x - 7 \amp= 1</mrow>
          <mrow>-8 \amp= x</mrow>
        </md>
        So, our second solution is <m>x = -8</m>.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li><p><alert>Graphical solution:</alert>  Let's check our solution, <m>x = -6</m> or <m>x = -8</m> graphically. To do this, we imagine that each part of our original expression has a  "<m>\color{red}{y = }</m> " in front of it. Then, we look for places on the graph of these two equations were both are true (i.e. where the two graphs intersect).</p>

    <sideBySide margins="5%" widths="30% 70%">
<div>
  <p>Enter the given expression to the left of the equals sign:</p> 
  <p><m>\color{red}{y = }</m><mathInput name="graphEq1" prefill="|x+7|"/></p>

  <p>Enter the given number to the right of the equals sign:</p> 
  <p><m>\color{red} {y = }</m><mathInput name="graphEq2" prefill="1"/></p>
  
  <p>First intersection point (drag or type):</p>
  <p><m>(x_1,y_1) =  </m></p>
  <p><m>\bigg(</m> <mathInput name="graphX1" bindValueTo="$p1.x"/> , <mathInput name="graphY1" bindValueTo="$graphEq2"/><m> \bigg)</m></p>
  <p>Second intersection point (drag or type):</p>
  <p><m>(x_2,y_2) =  </m></p>
  <p><m>\bigg(</m> <mathInput name="graphX2" bindValueTo="$p2.x"/> , <mathInput name="graphY2" bindValueTo="$graphEq2"/><m> \bigg)</m></p>
</div>

  
<graph name="g1">
  <rectangle fixed width="15" height="2" center="(0,-6)" styleNumber="13" filled/>
  <m anchor="(0,-6)" layer="2" fixed>{\large \text{drag points to the correct locations!}}</m>
  <function name="f">$graphEq1</function>
  <line name="line2" equation="y = $graphEq2" fixed styleNumber="2"/>
  <point name="p1" coords="(-1, $graphY1)" styleNumber="5">
    <constraints>
      <constrainToGrid/>
      <constrainTo>$line2</constrainTo>
    </constraints>
    <label>$p1.coords</label>
  </point>
  <point name="p2" coords="(1, $graphY2)" styleNumber="5">
    <label>$p2.coords</label>
    <constraints>
      <constrainToGrid/>
      <constrainTo>$line2</constrainTo>
    </constraints>
  </point>
</graph>
    </sideBySide>

    <p>Since the intersection points of the graph match the <m>x</m>-values from our algebraic solution, our work checks out!</p>
  </li>
</ul>
  
</example>
</div>
  
  </hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<p><m>x = $sol1</m> or <m>x = $sol2</m></p>
</solution>
</problem>



